T1  - Loan commitments, investment decisions and the signalling equilibrium
AU  - Duan, Jin-Chuan
AU  - Yoon, Suk Heun
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 17
IS  - 4
SP  - 645
EP  - 661
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/06/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(93)90005-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/037842669390005X
AB  - This paper analyzes the use of loan commitments to finance future risky investment projects. When the capital market is informed of a firm's project quality, having a loan commitment would lead the firm to overinvest. If banks are competitively rational, the cost of this overinvestment would be borne by the firm, making the loan commitment contract unattractive. When the project quality is private information, firms will signal their project qualities through purchasing loan commitments. This signal is credible because purchasing a loan commitment poses overinvestment cost to the firm. This paper establishes and characterizes this dissipative signalling equilibrium.
ER  - 

